string.value: The Nation with the most World Power Points at the end of the game wins.
The Alliance with the most World Power Points at the end of the game wins.
The Ideology with the most World Power Points at the end of the game wins.

Conscript Infantry are cheap and can be built quickly, but require more manpower than Basic Infantry and have no offensive capability. They are a useful option for nations with high populations and low industrial level cities. Can be built in any city.
Basic infantry are standard post WWI land forces equipped with basic weaponry. They cost more IPUs and can move faster than Conscript Infantry and require less manpower. Can be built in any city.

Better trained forces equipped with newer and better weapons. They are more effective against other ground forces than Basic Infantry, and have a very small chance to damage air units. Can be built in any city.
Highest quality ground troops with the best training and weapons. Increased effectiveness against ground forces and slightly higher chance to damage air units. Can be built in any city.

These post WWI tanks are the first basic armored units. Faster than infantry, they are not very accurate but do more damage than infantry when they do hit. Can only be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.

These standard WWII tanks are less armored but faster than other tanks. They cost less to build than their heavier cousins, and are reasonably accurate against ground forces. Can only be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.

The greatest feature of these tanks is that they have no outstanding features or weaknesses. They have very good accuracy, moderate cost, and decent speed. This makes them an excellent choice for almost any combat mission. Can only be built in Advanced cities.

These mammoth tanks are expensive and slower than their lighter cousins, but have superior accuracy. Their heavy armor allows them to absorb more punishment than the lighter tanks. Can only be built in Advanced cities.

These tanks reflect the technological advancements attained from all armored research. Although expensive, they have the accuracy of heavy tanks and do even more damage when they hit. Can only be built in Advanced cities.
Holdovers from WWI, Mounted Infantry quickly gave way to tanks and other armored vehicles. They are faster and more expensive than other infantry. Can be built in any city.
A superb combination of decent accuracy, low cost, and exceptional speed make Motorized Infantry a versatile and valuable land force. Can be built in any city.
These fast armored vehicles offer very good accuracy against ground forces combined with exceptional speed and a reasonable cost. Can only be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.

Field Artillery units are essentially infantry units with batteries of artillery and trucks to move them around. Although inexpensive to build, these basic units have a fair accuracy against land targets. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.

The first artillery unit with the ability to attack both land and air units with reasonable effectiveness, and the lowest IPU cost of any artillery capable of defending against aircraft. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.

Like its lighter cousin, this versatile unit has the ability to attack both land and air units with reasonable effectiveness. It is more expensive to build, but does much more damage than Light Artillery. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.

A hybrid of artillery and armor, this unit combines the versatility of artillery with the speed of armor. It is expensive to build, but highly accurate against land targets, if somewhat less so against aircraft. Can only be built in Advanced cities.

This artillery fires shells with self-contained propulsion, resulting in a high level of accuracy. It is very effective against land forces but is unable to attack aircraft. Can only be built in Advanced cities.

Designed in the mid 1930s these fighters are reasonably effective when used to defend against bomber attacks, engage fighters, and have minimal ability to attack targets on the ground. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.

These fighters have improved range and accuracy in air combat. They can be used to support ground troops with air cover, to engage incoming fighters and bombers, or escort friendly bombers to the target. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.

These fighters have superior range and attack capability. Their abilities make these aircraft useful in battle, as bomber escorts, or as battle-capable recon planes. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.
The first generation of Jet Fighters have far higher air combat ability than any other aircraft, and fair ability to attack ground units. Can only be built in Advanced cities.

These planes are the primary ground attack aircraft in the game, with the best chance to hit land or sea units. Their small payloads make them less effective against cities. Can only be built in Industrial or Advanced cities.

Still relatively inexpensive, these units are best used attacking cities or infrastructure. When paired with advanced fighters, their matching ranges allow them to fly complete missions with fighter protection. Can only be built in Advanced Cities.

Long range aircraft with enough air defense capability to risk flying without full fighter escort. Excellent chance to successfully attack cities, lesser chance against land forces. Can only be built in Advanced Cities.
High altitude long-range bombers that deliver superior attack capability against cities. Good air defense and moderate ground attack capability. Can only be built in Advanced Cities.

Often old, refurbished WWI era ships, they are very tough, reasonably fast and can inflict significant damage. Decent attack capability against other ships, and minor defense against air attacks. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced port cities.

Very tough and reasonably fast. Very good attack capability against other ships, and improved defense against air attacks. Large damage inflicted on anything it hits. Can only be built in Advanced port cities.

Extremely tough and reasonably fast. Superior attack capability against other ships, and good defense against air attacks. Major damage inflicted on anything it hits. Can only be built in Advanced port cities.
Vessels with moderate combat ability against ships and minor air defense. Fairly inexpensive and tougher than destroyers, but slower. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced port cities.
Tough ship that's able to give and take significant damage. Very good ability against ships and improved air defense. Can only be built in Advanced port cities.
The largest cruiser unit, with increased combat abiltity against ships and planes. Can only be built in Advanced port cities.

First generation aircraft carrier -- mainly a flat deck laid over old battleship hulls. Decent sea attack capability with limited air range. Small number of fighters. Can only be built in Industrial or Advanced port cities.
Improved range and attack capabilities against cities and sea units. More fighters than early carriers. Can only be built in Industrial or Advanced port cities.

Usually found at the center of a task force, this vessel has improved range, combat ability, and damage against all targets, land, air, sea, and city. More expensive than previous carriers. Can only be built in Advanced port cities.

Huge, incredibly tough, with an extended range and many fighters, this carrier is the best possible weapon against other sea units. It can attack land and air units, and has increased damage against all targets. Can only be built in Advanced port cities.
Small, very fast gunships typically used as pickets or support ships. Moderate combat capability against ships and minor defense against air attacks. Can be built in any port city.
Large, easily produced gunships with very good combat ability against other ships, and minor defense against air attacks. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced port cities.

These large, easily produced gunships unfog submarines in the region they are in. Very good combat ability against other ships and improved air defense. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced port cities.
These units can remain hidden in a sea region with enemy ships. Quite slow, with a moderate chance to hit ships and cause significant damage. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced port cities.
These units can remain hidden in a sea region with enemy ships. Quite slow, with a very good chance to hit ships and cause devastating damage. Can be built in Industrial or Advanced port cities.
Initial nuclear research investments will bring scientists together in atomic research laboratories.
Continued investment in atomic research can lead to basic successes. Scientists will experiment with fission, separating uranium and creating uncontrolled chain reactions.
Investments in enrichment can produce uranium 235 and plutonium 239. These heavy elements can then be used in weapons research.

Following success with uranium enrichment, atomic research will focus on creating a fission bomb. If this project succeeds, the military will gain the use of a radically new, inconceivably powerful weapon.
Initial investments in rocketry will bring engineers and scientists together in research facilities.
Continued research will lead to the development of rocket engines and solid and liquid propellants. These engineering and chemical advances are essential to the military application of rocketry.

The successful merger of rocketry research with weaponry will result in Guided Missiles. These are cruise missiles, powered in-air by jet engines, and with a range of 250 miles. Guided Missiles are similar to the V-1 missiles developed by Germany in the 1940s.

Further developments in rocketry research can lead to Ballistic Missiles. Launched from the ground, these missiles have a range of 500 miles. They are similar to the German V-2 missiles developed in the 1940s.
Intercontinental Ballistic Missiles (ICBMs) have more power and a larger range than regular ballistic missiles. ICBMs can travel over a thousand miles.
Initial investments in jet propulsion will bring engineers and scientists together in jet research facilities.
Continued research can lead to the development of jet engines and, subsequently, Jet Fighters. These planes are markedly faster than Advanced Planes.
Investment into vehicle radios will advance military communication and tactics.
Radar uses radio waves to detect objects and determine their direction, distance, and/or speed.
Sonar uses sound waves to detect submarines.
Amphibious assault tactics increase attack abilities for sea to land operations.
Mountain warfare tactics increase infantry units' effectiveness when they fight in mountainous terrain.
Jungle warfare tactics increase infantry units' effectiveness when they fight in jungle terrain.
Maneuver warfare is a theory of warfare that advocates shock and disruption. These tactics defeat adversaries by incapacitating their decision-making abilities.

Infiltration tactics involve small, lightly-equipped infantry forces attacking enemy rear areas. These tactics isolate strong enemy front lines and subject them to attack by follow-up friendly troops with heavier weapons.

Combined arms tactics coordinate different branches of a military to achieve greater success. This unified command structure increases overall military effectiveness, and is similar to the blitzkrieg strategy developed by Germany.
Attrition Warfare tactics strengthen army defenses. The enemy can be worn down by draining, continued battles.

Deep Defenses include trenches, foxholes, and machine gun nests. Defenders will hold a position till the situation becomes critical, and then withdraw towards positions that have been prepared before the assault.

Hedgehog Defenses are anti-blitzkrieg maneuvers, designed to combat combined arms tactics. Defenders deploy in heavily fortified positions. Attackers can penetrate between these 'hedgehogs', but each defense position continues to fight when surrounded.
The Fischer-Tropsch process uses coal to produce a synthetic oil substitute.
Hydrogenation plants use coal to produce synthetic oil, but with a better coal-to-oil ratio than the Fischer-Tropsch process.
Fuel additives increase the performance of synthetic fuels.
Automated targeting increases the accuracy of anti-air weapons by calculating aim points for firing.
Improved carrier fighters improve operational range and combat effectiveness.
Advanced carrier fighters further improve operational range and combat effectiveness.
Improved combat effectiveness for Armored and Motorized Vehicles.
Improved combat effectiveness for sea to land units
Increased combat strength for Infantry fighting in mountainous regions
Increased combat strength for Infantry fighting in jungle regions

The Student Report contains summaries of the game you've selected for review. You can examine your decisions, world events, conversations, comments, and more. These reports are valuable for assessing and reflecting on your Making History experience.
To create a Student Report, click Run. When the report is ready, you can view it by clicking on the Making History Reports icon or by going directly to the location below. Once you have opened your report folder, select index.html to access your report.

The Teacher Report contains summaries of the game you've selected for review. You can examine your students' decisions, world events, conversations, comments, and more. These reports are valuable for analyzing and assessing your students' Making History experiences.
To create a Teacher Report, click Run. When the report is ready, you can view it by clicking on the Making History Reports icon or by going directly to the location below. Once you have opened the report folder, select index.html to access the report.

Offering Wilno, Podesi and Tarnopol to the USSR may improve relations between your two countries.

Support an Austrian National Socialist Party coup, and send the Wehrmacht to enforce it if necessary.
Allow Austria to vote on its own independence.
Austrians are culturally German. Fascist political elements in Austria desire to become part of a greater Germany. However, annexing Austria could worsen our relations with other powers.
Surrender control of the government to Germany.
Austrians are culturally German. Fascist political elements in Austria desire to become part of a greater Germany.
Forfeit Austrian independence and become part of greater Germany.
Order the Austrian Army to resist the invading Wehrmacht.
Germany has supported a Fascist coup by the Austrian National Socialist Party. They threaten to send military force if we do not surrender power immediately.
The Austrians have rejected union with Germany. We must resolve this crisis by force if necessary.
Austria resists our coup attempt. We have no choice but to take their territory by force.

You demand that Czechoslovakia give Germany the Sudetenland. The Czechoslovaks will look to France and the UK for support, but you believe the French and British prefer diplomacy to war. They will not interfere with your plans.
You reject diplomatic methods. War will bring you what you want. The Sudetenland, and all Czechoslovakia, will fall to German might.
Controlling the Sudetenland is the first step in your plan to dominate Europe. Will you demand that Czechoslovakia cede the territory to Germany or will you simply declare war?
By transferring the Sudetenland, Czechoslovakia will avoid war with Germany. This can preserve the peace for all Europe.
Defend Czechoslovakia and declare war against Germany.
Germany should not be allowed to dominate Europe. You will reject this demand and declare war on Germany.

Germany has demanded the Czechoslovakian Sudetenland. If the Czechoslovaks do not transfer the territory, Germany will almost surely declare war. How should our nation respond? Will you defend Czechoslovakia or arrange a peaceful transfer of territory?

Czechoslovakia has agreed to Germany's demand. The Sudetenland region is now owned by Germany. Britain and France approved this transfer of territory. Their diplomatic maneuvers have weakened Czechoslovakia, but maintained peace in Europe.
Conquering Czechoslovakia is still on Germany's agenda, but you will keep the peace for now. You will declare war when it suits your needs.
Now is the time to attack. France and Britain did not stop you from acquiring the Sudetenland; you doubt they will stop you from conquering Czechoslovakia.

You successfully acquired the Sudetenland, but Germany has greater ambitions. Will you keep the peace and continue strengthening Germany? Or, will you seize the moment and declare war on Czechoslovakia?
Seize Hungarian lands currently controlled by the Czechs
Your involvement would only make the German-Czechoslovak conflict larger and messier. If you stay out, then hopefully the war will be small and fast.
You must respond to German belligerence. The Nazis cannot be allowed to destroy Europe. You will declare war against Germany, and support Czechoslovakia in its fight.
Germany has declared war against Czechoslovakia. How should you respond? Will Germany stop at the Czechoslovak borders or will the Nazis march all over Europe?
